erage agent tracks calls made during the test task, but the MethodHandle invoked a method in a dependency jar, which should still be reachable. However, it may be bypassing JaCoCo. Also, there could be issues with reflections or native images affecting the coverage results.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Addressing test failure**\\n\\nI'm focusing on fixing the test failure by removing the Groovy static dispatch test, but the task is to improve the situation. I could try to instantiate the closure with doCall. It seems the class$ method isn’t being utilized in the normal closure code because it relies on the ldc class for StringUtils and NoParameterValue. The class$ method looks like it's a legacy artifact, not invoked. I need to check if forcing the generated call site array initialization in the closure helps, as javap indicates a different initialization method.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating Java class access**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out why I can't see the `class$` method in the Java source. It seems like Java identifiers can include `$`, but maybe the method isn't in the original jar that’s compiled; it might only appear in the jacoco effective class generated after instrumentation. I'm thinking that maybe I used javap incorrectly, looking at the build/jacoco/effective folder. I need to check the original class compile classpath and see if I can locate the jar in Gradle or dependency cache.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_sZjJC44c6TLeNIp4CsvfDp7V|fc_08b4bac438a5c09d016a00dc58849881a381f4d4359d90bdbc", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0 -type f \\( -name 'rest-assured-5.5.0.jar' -o -name 'RequestSpecificationImpl$_generateRequestUriForLogging_closure14.class' \\) -print"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 6098, "output": 720, "cacheRead": 44032, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 50850, "cost": {"input": 0